.TH "HTMLOUTPUTELEMENT.HTMLFOR" "3JS" "November 25, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
HTMLOutputElement.htmlFor \- HTMLOutputElement: htmlFor property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The read\-only \f[B]\f[CB]htmlFor\f[B]\f[R] property of the
\f[CR]HTMLOutputElement\f[R] returns a live \f[CR]DOMTokenList\f[R]
object containing a list of \f[CR]id\f[R]s of those elements
contributing input values to (or otherwise affected) the calculation.
It reflects the \f[CR]<output>\f[R] element\(cqs \f[CR]for\f[R] content
attribute.
.SH VALUE
A live \f[CR]DOMTokenList\f[R] object.
.PP
Although the \f[CR]htmlFor\f[R] property itself is read\-only in the
sense that you can\(cqt replace the \f[CR]DOMTokenList\f[R] object, you
can still assign to the \f[CR]htmlFor\f[R] property directly, which is
equivalent to assigning to its \f[CR]value\f[R] property.
You can also modify the \f[CR]DOMTokenList\f[R] object using the
\f[CR]add()\f[R], \f[CR]remove()\f[R], \f[CR]replace()\f[R], and
\f[CR]toggle()\f[R] methods.
.SH EXAMPLES
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] outputElem = document.getElementById(\(dqresult\(dq);
\f[B]for\f[R] (\f[B]const\f[R] id \f[B]of\f[R] outputElem.htmlFor.split(\(dq \(dq)) {
  \f[B]const\f[R] elem = document.getElementById(id);
  elem.style.outline = \(dq2px solid red\(dq;
}
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]<output>\f[R]
